<paper id="1569530399"><title>The Observational Power of Clocks</title><year>1994</year><authors><author org="AT&amp;T Bell Lab.#TAB#" id="689646243">Rajeev Alur</author><author org="UNIVERSITY OF CRETE" id="349100197">Costas Courcoubetis</author><author org="Cornell University;" id="2707196735">Thomas A. Henzinger</author></authors><n_citation>59</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>3820865</reference><reference>1563480347</reference><reference>1574289075</reference><reference>1599105192</reference><reference>1600541802</reference><reference>1755579963</reference><reference>1865562238</reference><reference>1981808971</reference><reference>2011694130</reference><reference>2025079043</reference><reference>2025782239</reference><reference>2030263557</reference><reference>2093045165</reference><reference>2101508170</reference><reference>2153273838</reference><reference>2167668895</reference></references><venue id="1145706541" type="C">International Conference on Concurrency Theory</venue><doi>10.1007/978-3-540-48654-1_16</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.48446">Transition system</keyword><keyword weight="0.37146">Observational study</keyword><keyword weight="0.46642">Arbitrary-precision arithmetic</keyword><keyword weight="0.41544">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.44056">Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.43079">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.56665">Equivalence (measure theory)</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Time difference</keyword><keyword weight="0.5903">Observer (quantum physics)</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We develop a theory of equivalences for timed systems. Two systems are equivalent iff external observers cannot observe differences in their behavior. The notion of equivalence depends, therefore, on the distinguishing power of the observers. The power of an observer to measure time results in untimed, clock, and timed equivalences: an untimed observer cannot measure the time difference between events; a clock observer uses a clock to measure time differences with finite precision; a timed observer is able to measure time differences with arbitrary precision.</abstract></paper>